<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>PFS Draft Submission</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Principal Forensic Services Ltd (PFS) (FSS004)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Declaration of Interests</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Principal Forensic Services Ltd (PFS) is a private limited company; its business is provision of forensic science related advice, consultancy, case</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> review and training. C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">asework services are provided to both prosecution and defence, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">consultancy services to all parts of the industry and Governments, in the UK and abroad. In addition to casework and consultancy services, PFS is currently delivering work for the Forensic Science Regulator. Although all PFS members were formerly employed by FSS, we do not seek to represent FSS, and have focussed our submission on the current and future provision of forensic science, rather than on the past.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Does the Government have an effective strategy for forensic science in the UK and is it sufficient to support forensic science R&amp;D and criminal justice?</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We have seen no evidence of an effective Government strategy for forensic science in the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We understand that a new forensic science strategy gr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">oup, under the leadership of Mr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Stephen Webb, has recently been convened, but there is no evidence of this group having met regularly or produced substantive output. We are not aware of any requests for input from forensic experts.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The lack of forensic science strategy has led to a fragile market in forensic science, from which some Police Forces are aiming to insulate themselves by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">increased </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">insourcing of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">elements of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">forensic science provision: the largest scale example of this is within the Metropolitan Police Service</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (MPS)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. However, there is a lack of national consistency, with some forces continuing to outsource the majority of their forensic science work, and a marked variability in adherence to quality standards. We have seen no convincing business case supporting either insourcing or outsourcing, and while the lack of strategy and direction continues, the external forensic science market is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">at risk</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of collapse.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The National DNA Database (NDNAD) Strategy Board does meet quarterly and minutes are published. Review of these minutes suggests that the Board is not being provided with sufficiently up to date, relevant scientific advice. The NDNAD has fallen behind the state of the art (and indeed behind other countries), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">using</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> outdated technology for the analytical process of producing DNA profiles and failing to make optimal use of enhanced algorithms for searching crime scene profiles against the database. It is no exaggeration to say that as a result, investigative leads that could result in crimes being solved are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">being missed on a daily basis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Did the FSS transition and closure run smoothly and within budget?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is our understanding that the FSS transition was completed under budget, costing £78M against a budget of £120M. The professionalism of FSS staff enabled the closure to run smoothly, without </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> quality issues during an extremely difficult time. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is less clear if the £78M spent represented good value for money for the UK ta</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">x payer. W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e do not have a full picture</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of the cost </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or true</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> value </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for money </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of forensic science provision in the UK: CC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Sims has said that the private option has been cost effective</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">owever,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is unclear</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> whether this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is a comprehensive assessment including</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the continuing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> investment in Police </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">forensic facilities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and whether or not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a consequence of FSS closure or the direction in which forensic provision was in any case proceeding.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rom the current position, the most important question is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">what next?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> And will another major provider leave the market</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> if </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">revenues</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> continue to fall</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">? </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">What </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">strategy is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in place</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to ensure continuity of provision </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of forensic work and retention of skilled staff </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">if this were to happen?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What impacts have the FSS’s closure had on (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">) the criminal justice system and (ii) forensic science R&amp;D and training? In particular, have the appropriate quality standards and accreditation been rigorously maintained? </span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our answer focuses not on the FSS closure, since in our view this was a symptom of pre-existing problems in the forensic market and a lack of strategy for forensic science in the UK. Instead, we focus on the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">current situation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CJS</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Human error is a fact of life, and has happened within every forensic service provider (FSP), no matter how strong the quality system. However, in the past year, we</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> have seen </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">quality failure</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">which led to loss of liberty for an innocent man</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">; this has not been seen for very many years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Systems, when they fail, should “fail safe”: in forensic science this means that no failure of a system should ever result in the false inclusion of an innocent person. However, in the case of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mr Adam Scott, the erro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r made by LGC Forensics Ltd. le</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d to his sample falsely being associated with a rape case, and to his imprisonment for over 4 months. Although human error was identified as the cause of this catastrophic failing, it is our firm belief that the error could only have occurred within a system that was itself inadequate. Multiple opportunities to identify the error were missed. Further, we remain to be convinced that similar errors were not made in other cases during the same time period.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">LGC Forensics Ltd. has held ISO17025 accreditation for many years; the ISO17025 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">standard sets out </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">general requirements for the competence of testing and calibration laboratories</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and requires that laboratories validate systems and follow</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> documented protocols. The ability to recognise a failing in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> system, however, rests on validation and in-depth knowledge, and requires ownership and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">risk assessment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">within the accredited organisation. This error clearly illustrates that major quality failures can and do occur within accredited organisations.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">During the course of our work, we have observed other instances of poor quality, which we highlight briefly below:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Procurement led purely by Police leading to bias in wh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ich</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> examinations are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">commissioned in specific cases;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Poor handover between providers and poor communication of vital information, leading to incorrect assumptions being used, and therefore unsupportable opinions being offered in evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Use of un-validated methods</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Poor handling of evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Misidentification of drugs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Firearms classification cases being reported on by police armourers using unaccredited equipment and procedures;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Problems in the interpretation of results at the level required for court purposes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Problems in presentation of evidence in court, with inexperienced scientists providing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a confused picture to the jury;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Interim reports, marked clearly as being unsuited for evidential purposes, being produced as evidence.</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In a volatile market with more, smaller providers (both private and Police), fewer organisations have the depth and breadth of expertise required</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> not only to meet minimum standards, but to grow and develop these standards.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Forensic Science R&amp;D and Training</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although undoubtedly other organisations are involved in forensic science R&amp;D, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ata compiled b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y Thompson Reuters clearly show</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that in the period 2001 – 2011, FSS was the only UK organisation to feature in the top 25 forensic research organisations worldwide (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">at number 5, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">judged by number of citations), with a further 2 UK institutes (Universities of Oxford and Leicester) in this list when the journal impact factors were also considered. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We welcome initiatives to increase collaboration and communication between researchers in the field, such as the creation of a Special Interest Group in forensic science. However,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">there has been no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> compensat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for immediate loss of the c.£3-5M per annum invested </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in R&amp;D </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">by FSS, or the long-term impact of losing a top-5 worldwide research institute.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Critical to the future of forensic science research in the UK is the health of the forensic science market, a point made in evidence by several witnesses at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the last enquiry, including Mr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> David Richardson of LGC. It would be interesting to revisit the impact </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that continuing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">market </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">instability has</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> had on a forensic provider in the interim: Mr Richardson referred to over 70 research projects in LGC Forensics at that time, so it would be illuminating to know how many are actively continuing and what </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">novel science </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">has been implemented from this programme since the last enquiry.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Notwithstanding valuable work from FSPs and academics in forensic science R&amp;D, the current laissez-faire approach will not support major strategic changes, such as ensuring that forensic science capitalises on the genomics revolution. Nor will it enable the important task of developing and maintaining appropriate data collections to provide scientific calibration for forensic inference, a critical requirement pointed out both by the US National Academy of Sciences an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d the Court of Appeal in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Such work</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> falls outside the funding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> remit of the Research Councils, and does not lead to the type of publications necessary for academic researchers to obtain a favourable assessment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">under</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research Excellence Framework; i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> provides no </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">realistic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">prospect o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">f return on investment for FSP</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t is however </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">essential</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to the CJS.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The UK needs strategic leadership and vision to ensure a healthy future for forensic science, coupled with a modest level </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">structural funding to complement the work that can be funded through academic or commercial routes.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> We can learn from good practice in the USA, where strategically important technologies are championed across multiple Government Departments, with user requirements agreed by the Department of Justice, Department of Homeland Security and Department of Defence. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In relation to training, the quality failure in the case of Mr Scott must raise doubts in relation to the level of training of the staff involved. However, training a laboratory technician to follow a written method is a simple matter in comparison to the training that underpins an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">expert’s opinion: here, we refer also to our answer to question 7, regarding loss of intellectual wealth.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Nonetheless, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a positive sign of engagement of the forensic science community with the need for additional training that a workshop dealing with the management of contamination, run by the Forensic Science Society and delivered by Principal Forensic Services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> was over-subscribed.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What should be role of the Forensic Science Regulator?</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In addition to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">his role in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">definin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g standards covering the entire process</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> from crime scene to court, we believe that it is critical that the Forensic Science Regulator (FSR) be given statutory powers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and the necessary resources </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to ensure compliance with the standards.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The standards </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">set </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to date largely depend on ISO17025, which is a standard for testing and calibration laboratories. As such, it does not cover much of the interpretation of results or any of the presentation of evidence in courts. In a limited way, testing laboratories can opt to extend their ISO17025 accreditation to cover interpretation of results; however, this option is only open to testing laboratories already accredited for the analytical process of producing the result to be interpreted. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is a clear need for international standards to cover interpretation of results and expert opinion that does not exist solely as an optional add-on to those for laboratory testing. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The ISO17020 standard is likely to be implemented for scene of crime work in the future: having a defined quality standard for this part of the process would be a major step forward.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he Codes of Conduct published by the FSR are more wide ranging, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">especially as the appendices to this code continue to be developed. W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">fully </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">supportive of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the Codes and their</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> full implementation in as short a timescale as possible. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">current timescale set for compliance with the codes is not until October 2013 for some elements and October 2015 for the remainder. Despite this generous timescale, response has been very variable with some </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Police F</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">orces fully accepting that accreditation to quality standards is crucially important, whilst others lag far behind. Any further </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">financial pressures on police budgets</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> exacerba</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ting</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the view expressed by some that they “cannot afford to do quality”. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In our view, a critical further element where quality standards should be expanded is in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">relation to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the direction of scientific strategy within cases, so as to ensure that budgetary constraints</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Police priorities, whilst understandable and necessary,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> do not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">compromise the impartiality of case examination.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Such standards are also required in order to ensure that fragmentation of a case between Police and one or more FSPs does not adversely affect overall case strategy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the size of the forensics market and how stable is it?</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Market stability has two elements: </span></li></ol><ol type="I" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">What is the projected market size over the coming years?</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Will all of the major FSPs survive in the market, and if not, what impact would a second major exit have?</span></li></ol><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We do not have access to accurate figures for the size of the forensic market</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, although the ACPO lead for forensic science, CC Chris Sims, recently said </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it had</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> declined to less than £100M</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ach </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reduction</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in police budget has a disproportionately bigger impact on forensic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">spend, which is discretionary, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in comparison to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">many other parts of the police budget, for which costs are fixed.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Decreases in Crime Scene Investigator (CSI) attendance at crime scenes have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">recently been reported</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">During Operation Slingshot, a significant proportion of the work in the external forensic market was reallocated from FSS to other FSPs. Since that time, an even larger proportion of the market has been re-tendered, with not all of the outcomes yet known. What we do know, however, is that a large volume of work has once again changed hands between FSPs, leading to redundancies in at least one FSP an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d recruitment at another. M</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ajor swings in work volume between FSPs are damaging to long term investment in R&amp;D, professional development </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and retention of skilled staff </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and FSP financial stability.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In summary, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> market </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">has declined</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">markedly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">size</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and this trend appears to be continuing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Margins are slim,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">work </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">move</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s between providers every few years </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">with loss of skilled staff </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">each time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> either through redundancy or relocation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the reputation of a company can be destroyed in a ve</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ry public way with any error.  The largest private FSP, LGC Forensics, is owned by private equity firm </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Bridgepoint</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to answer the committee’s question on market stability, perhaps a view from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Bridgepoint</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> on the continued attractiveness of investing in UK forensic science </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">would assist</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How are forensic science services procured by police forces and could procurement processes be improved?</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We note that the NE Police Forces have opted out of the National Forensic Science Procurement Framework, tendering separately for their forensic science provision: we do not have information on their reasons, and any impact on the National Framework.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We have mentioned elsewhere in our submission the contribution that regular major changes in work volume between FSPs make to risk in relation to market instability, long term investment and professional development and retention of scientists. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In some instances, large contracts are awarded to an FSP before they have acquired the equipment or established the capability to offer the service: sub-contracting is often used to bridge the gap, and we have concerns about the application of standards when analytical work is further sub-contracted, for example to University laboratories</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> who may not have the necessary specialised facilities and expertise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We have also discussed the influence that Police priorities can have on case strategy when forensic science is procured from a “menu” of defined products: the needs of the final end user of the outputs from forensic science, the Courts, must be considered alongside Police priorities if the process is to meet the needs of the entire CJS.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> A partnership approach to establishing case strategy will produce better outcomes than if the choice of examinations is made purely by either Police or FSP.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We would like to see the procurement process provide stronger incentives for FSPs to invest in R&amp;D, and an improved collaborative approach to establishing opportunities and requirements for research, rather than</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aggressive intellectual property ownership clauses: FSPs operate in a commercial market, and must be enabled to exploit the outcomes of their R&amp;D investment beyond the life of any particular contract.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Has the closure of the FSS resulted in a loss of intellectual wealth through its scientists leaving the forensic science profession, or the UK? (please provide evidence/examples)</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Most</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">FSS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-siz