15%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Approximately </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">70% of the country’s forensic toxicology expertise was lost. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It was ironic that on the day the FSS London toxicology unit was closed, a Home office representative expressed concern about the loss of toxicology provision. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">New </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">staff </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are being recruited by some FSPs but all require training and it will be many years until the knowledge gap has been filled. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Of 10 Reporting Officers in the FSS London v</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">olume crime marks and traces team</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">one</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> was transferred to the MPS under TUPE, 4 are opera</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ting as independent consultants</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the remaining </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">5 have left forensic science completely.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A number of the FSS staff </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">who moved</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to LGC are now </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">being made redundant.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Many former FSS staff are consulting; we believe that few consultancies will survive in the longer term.</span></li></ul><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However, looking at just numbers of scientists still in forensic science is misleading</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the new operating model implemented by the MPS has different skill requirements, and many scientists who transferred to the MPS under TUPE are using only a subset of their previous skill</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">et</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In particular, interpretation of complex DNA profiles is no longer a requirement for these previously skilled experts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> who</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> will lose this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">expertise now that they are not actively practising</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Principal Forensic Services (PFS) consists of 15 of the most skilled and experienced forensic scientists in the UK. It was formed by the Principal Forensic Scientists of FSS, who were </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the leading FSS experts in each forensic discipline, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">responsible for setting scientific and quality standards, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">working</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> on some of the most challenging cases and problems encountered in forensic science</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Many have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">achieved world-wide recognition. In forming PFS, we aimed to retain this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">exceptional concentration of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">expertise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. However, whilst our business is growing, we caution against the continuing trend for organisations in the CJS to rely on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">pro bono</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> advice: the expertise will be lost from forensic science unless the scientists are able to make a living.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are current arrangements for the FSS’s archives satisfactory? How could arrangements for the retention of case files and forensic materials in the UK be improved?</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The FSS archive supports only past FSS cases. All current and future archives will be fragmented between multiple providers and Police Forces</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, making it difficult to locate the appropriate route for tracing specific </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">casefiles</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and samples</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. We urge the Government to invest in cr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">eation of a national, searcha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ble archive, backed by support from experienced scientists with the knowledge of historic methods and quality standards, to enable the archive to b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e used intelligently. Standards are required, which should detail what should be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tained,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> how </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it should be retained and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> who should have access to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2013</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.policeoracle.com/news/Crime/2012/Dec/18/Forensics-Changing-Landscape-Heralds-New-Era_59152.html</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.policeoracle.com/news/Crime/2012/Dec/18/Forensics-Changing-Landscape-Heralds-New-Era_59152.html</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> BBC news, 17 December 2012</span></p></body></html>